Montevideo’s autonomist projects. These transimperial networks offered different political, social, and economic options to local societies and shaped the politics that emerged in the region, including the formation of Uruguay. Connecting South America to the broader Atlantic World, this book provides an excellent case study for examining the significance of cross-border interactions in shaping independence processes and political identities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh  a18th century.  a19th century south america.  aargentina.  aargentinian commerce.  aatlantic trade.  abanda oriental.  acisplatine province.  acolonia do sacramento.  acommerce in the south atlantic.  adon manuel cipriano de melo.  aeconomic history of argentina.  aluso brazilians.  amontevideo.  aportuguese imperialism.  ario de la plata.  asouth america.  asouth american history.  aspanish conquest in south america.  atransatlantic trade.  atransimperial trade.  auruguay.  awar in the south atlantic.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028515640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096073240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520960732423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520960732/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY